00:00:47.570 --> 00:00:50.480
So in the lecture that I just
completed a few moments ago,

00:00:50.480 --> 00:00:53.480
we described--

00:00:53.480 --> 00:00:57.980
I described how to characterize
the gauge-invariant radiative

00:00:57.980 --> 00:01:01.355
degrees of freedom, which we
call gravitational radiation.

00:01:01.355 --> 00:01:04.400
With gravitational radiation,
we found at the end--

00:01:04.400 --> 00:01:06.830
there's a formula that I will
write down again a little

00:01:06.830 --> 00:01:08.960
bit later in this lecture,
but we essentially

00:01:08.960 --> 00:01:14.300
found that it looks like certain
projections of a term that

00:01:14.300 --> 00:01:18.255
involves two time derivatives
of the quadrupole moment

00:01:18.255 --> 00:01:18.755
of a source.

00:01:21.340 --> 00:01:26.500
This has in recent
years led to a--

00:01:26.500 --> 00:01:28.600
well, we've now been
able to directly measure

00:01:28.600 --> 00:01:30.040
this form of radiation.

00:01:30.040 --> 00:01:35.528
I'm wearing my LIGO hat in
honor of the facility that first

00:01:35.528 --> 00:01:36.820
directly measured these things.

00:01:36.820 --> 00:01:39.160
And we have inaugurated
an entirely new field

00:01:39.160 --> 00:01:42.442
of observational
astronomy based on being

00:01:42.442 --> 00:01:43.650
able to measure those things.

00:01:46.190 --> 00:01:48.160
It's pretty exciting.

00:01:48.160 --> 00:01:51.560
I hope, though,
that a few people

00:01:51.560 --> 00:01:56.030
noticed how restricted the
analysis that I did is.

00:01:56.030 --> 00:01:59.240
I defined gravitational
waves only

00:01:59.240 --> 00:02:06.540
in the context of linearized
theory on a flat background.

00:02:06.540 --> 00:02:09.335
We haven't talked much
about other solutions

00:02:09.335 --> 00:02:13.880
to the Einstein field equations
yet, but you know it's coming.

00:02:13.880 --> 00:02:18.440
And I hope you can appreciate
that, in fact, our universe is

00:02:18.440 --> 00:02:21.620
not described by
a flat background.

00:02:21.620 --> 00:02:25.250
Many of the sources
that we study,

00:02:25.250 --> 00:02:28.045
it is only weakly curved
away from a flat background.

00:02:28.045 --> 00:02:29.420
So for instance,
our solar system

00:02:29.420 --> 00:02:31.837
is accurately described as
something that is weakly curved

00:02:31.837 --> 00:02:33.910
away from a flat background.

00:02:33.910 --> 00:02:36.760
And in that context,
much of what I described

00:02:36.760 --> 00:02:38.470
carries over very cleanly.

00:02:38.470 --> 00:02:40.510
And so you essentially have--

00:02:40.510 --> 00:02:42.190
in that case, you need to--

00:02:42.190 --> 00:02:44.440
if you want to analyze things
like gravitational waves

00:02:44.440 --> 00:02:47.980
propagating in our solar system
or through a galaxy which

00:02:47.980 --> 00:02:52.870
has a spacetime metric, it's
also accurately described

00:02:52.870 --> 00:02:56.680
as flat spacetime plus a
weak deviation away from it.

00:02:56.680 --> 00:02:58.183
You can take
advantage of the fact

00:02:58.183 --> 00:02:59.600
that your gravitational
wave tends

00:02:59.600 --> 00:03:02.260
to be something
that's rapidly varying

00:03:02.260 --> 00:03:04.240
and your solar system
and your galaxy

00:03:04.240 --> 00:03:06.550
is something that has
very slow time variation,

00:03:06.550 --> 00:03:07.888
or it's even static.

00:03:07.888 --> 00:03:09.430
So you can take
advantage of the fact

00:03:09.430 --> 00:03:10.805
that there's these
different time

00:03:10.805 --> 00:03:13.690
derivatives to separate terms.

00:03:13.690 --> 00:03:15.310
That actually leads
me naturally to,

00:03:15.310 --> 00:03:17.260
what do we do if
I want to describe

00:03:17.260 --> 00:03:21.040
the very realistic scenario of
gravitational waves propagating

00:03:21.040 --> 00:03:22.990
not on a flat background,
but on some kind

00:03:22.990 --> 00:03:24.700
of a curved background?

00:03:24.700 --> 00:03:27.610
Perhaps they propagate
near a black hole

00:03:27.610 --> 00:03:30.690
where spacetime is very
different from the spacetime

00:03:30.690 --> 00:03:31.927
of special relativity.

00:03:31.927 --> 00:03:33.760
Perhaps we need to
describe them propagating

00:03:33.760 --> 00:03:36.880
across a large sector
of our universe.

00:03:36.880 --> 00:03:38.530
We haven't talked
about cosmology yet,

00:03:38.530 --> 00:03:42.430
but it's the subject of the
next lecture I intend to record.

00:03:42.430 --> 00:03:47.200
And the spacetime that describes
our universe on large scales

00:03:47.200 --> 00:03:50.570
does not look like the
metric of special relativity.

00:03:50.570 --> 00:04:00.680
So how do I describe
gravitational radiation, GWs,

00:04:00.680 --> 00:04:07.750
Gravitational Waves, on
a non-flat background?

00:04:15.150 --> 00:04:19.110
Schematically, you can
imagine that in this case,

00:04:19.110 --> 00:04:22.440
you're working with
a spacetime that can

00:04:22.440 --> 00:04:27.143
be broken into a background.

00:04:27.143 --> 00:04:29.310
I'll put a little hat on
it to say that this denotes

00:04:29.310 --> 00:04:30.972
my background spacetime.

00:04:33.570 --> 00:04:35.850
And then some kind of a wave
field propagating on it.

00:04:38.920 --> 00:04:41.890
This background
is no longer going

00:04:41.890 --> 00:04:43.330
to be that of
special relativity.

00:04:43.330 --> 00:04:45.520
This could be
something that varies

00:04:45.520 --> 00:04:46.660
with both space and time.

00:04:58.970 --> 00:05:07.020
This will be something that in
general is small in the sense

00:05:07.020 --> 00:05:10.320
that in most of the cases,
certainly all the cases

00:05:10.320 --> 00:05:12.220
we're going to
study in this class,

00:05:12.220 --> 00:05:14.220
any term that involves
an h times an h

00:05:14.220 --> 00:05:17.910
will be second order
in a very small number,

00:05:17.910 --> 00:05:20.123
and so we can discard it.

00:05:20.123 --> 00:05:22.290
But it's still going to be
challenging to figure out

00:05:22.290 --> 00:05:27.240
how I can even define what
a wave means in this case.

00:05:30.300 --> 00:05:31.930
So to wrap your
heads around that,

00:05:31.930 --> 00:05:34.690
think about what a local
measurement might do, OK?

00:05:34.690 --> 00:05:38.150
So suppose I am in some
region of spacetime.

00:05:38.150 --> 00:05:40.422
So first of all,
we had a parable

00:05:40.422 --> 00:05:42.130
that we looked at in
our previous lecture

00:05:42.130 --> 00:05:45.490
where we looked at geodesics
in a spacetime that was flat

00:05:45.490 --> 00:05:48.100
plus a gravitational wave.

00:05:48.100 --> 00:05:50.610
And of course,
geodesics are geodesics,

00:05:50.610 --> 00:05:53.020
and so we just found that they
are unaccelerated relative

00:05:53.020 --> 00:05:54.040
to freefall frames.

00:05:54.040 --> 00:05:57.040
That sort of is-- you
know, more or less

00:05:57.040 --> 00:06:00.850
defines what a geodesic is,
so it was not too surprising.

00:06:00.850 --> 00:06:03.250
But we can then look at,
for example, two relatively

00:06:03.250 --> 00:06:04.960
nearby geodesics,
and we can look

00:06:04.960 --> 00:06:07.300
at how their geodesic
separation changes.

00:06:07.300 --> 00:06:08.860
We can look at the
behavior of light

00:06:08.860 --> 00:06:11.050
as it bounces back and forth.

00:06:11.050 --> 00:06:12.860
Something that's
important to bear in mind

00:06:12.860 --> 00:06:14.560
is that when I make
a measurement like

00:06:14.560 --> 00:06:20.760
that, I measure this
or some quantity that

00:06:20.760 --> 00:06:22.830
is derived from this,
the curvature tensor

00:06:22.830 --> 00:06:26.490
or an integrated light
propagation time.

00:06:36.710 --> 00:06:40.430
We may know that
the spacetime metric

00:06:40.430 --> 00:06:44.398
has two vary conceptually
different contributions to it.

00:06:44.398 --> 00:06:46.190
It's got a background,
and it's got a wave.

00:06:52.480 --> 00:06:56.300
How do we-- conceptually, we
might see how to separate them,

00:06:56.300 --> 00:07:03.790
but how do we define some
kind of a toolkit that

00:07:03.790 --> 00:07:06.610
allows us to separate?

00:07:06.610 --> 00:07:11.560
How do we define the separation
between background and wave?

00:07:17.518 --> 00:07:18.310
Put it another way.

00:07:18.310 --> 00:07:21.263
Suppose what you are sensitive
to is spacetime curvature.

00:07:21.263 --> 00:07:22.930
Suppose you are
sensitive to things that

00:07:22.930 --> 00:07:25.090
depend on the Riemann tensor.

00:07:25.090 --> 00:07:28.120
How do you know from your
measurement that you are

00:07:28.120 --> 00:07:31.240
measuring the Riemann tensor
associated to the gravitational

00:07:31.240 --> 00:07:34.020
wave and not a Riemann tensor
associated with a curvature--

00:07:34.020 --> 00:07:34.560
excuse me--

00:07:34.560 --> 00:07:37.840
associated with your background?

00:07:37.840 --> 00:07:43.070
That is an extremely
important issue.

00:07:43.070 --> 00:07:46.357
If all I can measure is
this, but I want to get this,

00:07:46.357 --> 00:07:48.940
what is the trick that I use to
distinguish between these two?

00:07:56.420 --> 00:07:58.008
I call this a trick
in my notes, but I

00:07:58.008 --> 00:07:59.300
don't like that term, actually.

00:07:59.300 --> 00:08:00.380
This is not a trick.

00:08:00.380 --> 00:08:03.560
This is a fundamentally
important point

00:08:03.560 --> 00:08:07.250
when you are trying to measure
some kind of a perturbation

00:08:07.250 --> 00:08:08.450
to a--

00:08:08.450 --> 00:08:10.918
not just to spacetime,
but to any kind of a field

00:08:10.918 --> 00:08:12.710
that you are studying,
any kind of quantity

00:08:12.710 --> 00:08:15.440
you're studying which is
itself spatially and temporally

00:08:15.440 --> 00:08:18.110
varying.

00:08:18.110 --> 00:08:25.670
What you need to do is take
advantage of a separation

00:08:25.670 --> 00:08:28.023
of length and timescales.

00:08:46.270 --> 00:08:48.040
When I'm talking about
general relativity

00:08:48.040 --> 00:08:50.560
and I'm talking about
gravitational waves,

00:08:50.560 --> 00:08:55.250
I am going to use the fact
that a gravitational wave is

00:08:55.250 --> 00:08:56.441
oscillatory.

00:09:01.260 --> 00:09:16.610
And as such, it varies on a much
smaller length and timescales--

00:09:16.610 --> 00:09:21.020
it varies on much smaller
length and timescales

00:09:21.020 --> 00:09:22.290
than the background does.

00:09:34.170 --> 00:09:35.190
OK?

00:09:35.190 --> 00:09:37.620
It's useful to introduce
an analogy here.

00:09:37.620 --> 00:09:42.450
Think about a water wave
propagating on the ocean.

00:09:49.650 --> 00:09:51.370
In almost all
cases when you look

00:09:51.370 --> 00:09:53.200
at a water wave
propagating on the ocean,

00:09:53.200 --> 00:09:56.770
it's obvious what
is the wave and what

00:09:56.770 --> 00:09:59.147
is the curvature in the ocean.

00:09:59.147 --> 00:10:00.730
It's actually
associated with the fact

00:10:00.730 --> 00:10:03.580
that the Earth is round.

00:10:03.580 --> 00:10:07.120
So it is clear from the
separation of both length

00:10:07.120 --> 00:10:08.635
scales and timescales--

00:10:08.635 --> 00:10:19.650
not clean-- clear
how to separate wave

00:10:19.650 --> 00:10:30.810
from the curvature
of the Earth bending

00:10:30.810 --> 00:10:37.710
due to geological structures
and things like that.

00:10:43.880 --> 00:10:46.450
A component of the
curvature of the ocean

00:10:46.450 --> 00:10:50.322
that has a curvature scale
of, say, 6,000 kilometers--

00:10:50.322 --> 00:10:52.030
well, that's just the
fact that the Earth

00:10:52.030 --> 00:10:54.050
is a sphere with a radius
of 6,000 kilometers.

00:10:54.050 --> 00:10:54.550
OK?

00:10:54.550 --> 00:10:55.750
So you can kind of see that.

00:10:55.750 --> 00:10:57.550
But if you see something
that is varying

00:10:57.550 --> 00:10:59.133
with a period of
about a second that's

00:10:59.133 --> 00:11:01.120
got a wavelength
of a meter or two,

00:11:01.120 --> 00:11:03.412
that has nothing to do with
the curvature of the Earth.

00:11:03.412 --> 00:11:05.200
That's a wave.

00:11:05.200 --> 00:11:08.980
We want to introduce a similar
concept here and apply it

00:11:08.980 --> 00:11:12.100
to our general
relativistic calculation.

00:11:12.100 --> 00:11:24.190
So let's introduce two sets
of length and timescales--

00:11:24.190 --> 00:11:26.800
let's call them scales--

00:11:26.800 --> 00:11:28.180
we will use in our analysis.

00:11:38.240 --> 00:11:44.470
So capital L and
capital T, these

00:11:44.470 --> 00:11:46.780
are my long length
in timescales.

00:11:54.360 --> 00:11:59.725
These describe the
variation of my background.

00:12:06.860 --> 00:12:14.260
Lambda and tau are
my short scales,

00:12:14.260 --> 00:12:24.980
and they describe the
wavelength in the period

00:12:24.980 --> 00:12:27.090
of gravitational waves.

00:12:27.090 --> 00:12:29.990
So to put this in the context
of the kind of measurements

00:12:29.990 --> 00:12:35.550
that LIGO makes, the
LIGO interferometers

00:12:35.550 --> 00:12:40.200
make measurements
of behavior of light

00:12:40.200 --> 00:12:43.080
moving in the spacetime
near the Earth.

00:12:43.080 --> 00:12:44.760
Now, there is a
component of that

00:12:44.760 --> 00:12:48.480
that varies on a
scale that has to do

00:12:48.480 --> 00:12:52.500
with the curvature of spacetime
near the surface of the Earth

00:12:52.500 --> 00:12:55.470
due to the Earth's
mass distribution.

00:12:55.470 --> 00:12:58.060
That occurs on--
so first of all,

00:12:58.060 --> 00:13:00.870
that is practically static.

00:13:00.870 --> 00:13:04.320
It does vary somewhat
because of the motion

00:13:04.320 --> 00:13:07.860
of the moon around
the Earth and because

00:13:07.860 --> 00:13:12.890
of the behavior of the
fluid in the Earth's core.

00:13:12.890 --> 00:13:16.740
There are small variations there
which, interestingly enough,

00:13:16.740 --> 00:13:18.630
can be measured.

00:13:18.630 --> 00:13:20.940
But those tend to
occur on timescales

00:13:20.940 --> 00:13:24.150
on the order of hours
at the shortest.

00:13:24.150 --> 00:13:26.250
For the moon's orbit,
the moon goes around

00:13:26.250 --> 00:13:29.070
in a time period
of about a month.

00:13:29.070 --> 00:13:32.180
The Earth's rotating.

00:13:32.180 --> 00:13:33.780
It's turning on its axis.

00:13:33.780 --> 00:13:35.520
And so at a particular
point, you're

00:13:35.520 --> 00:13:40.320
sort of casing the gravitational
field of the moon as the Earth

00:13:40.320 --> 00:13:44.370
rotates under it, and
so your time thing here

00:13:44.370 --> 00:13:47.940
is on the order of
hours to about a day.

00:13:47.940 --> 00:13:50.040
The length scale
associated with this--

00:13:50.040 --> 00:13:52.320
you can calculate things
like the Riemann curvature

00:13:52.320 --> 00:13:55.560
or tensor components near
the surface of the Earth.

00:13:55.560 --> 00:13:58.390
That has the units of
1 over length squared.

00:13:58.390 --> 00:14:00.630
So take the square
root and inverse it,

00:14:00.630 --> 00:14:03.000
and you're going to find
that this varies on a length

00:14:03.000 --> 00:14:05.978
scale that is thousands or--

00:14:05.978 --> 00:14:08.520
I should probably work this out
before I try quoting numbers,

00:14:08.520 --> 00:14:12.150
but it's many, many, many,
many, many kilometers,

00:14:12.150 --> 00:14:16.050
tens of thousands or
millions of kilometers.

00:14:16.050 --> 00:14:17.760
Tens of thousands, probably.

00:14:17.760 --> 00:14:20.310
My gravitational
wave, by contrast,

00:14:20.310 --> 00:14:23.220
it's got wavelengths that
are on the order of-- they

00:14:23.220 --> 00:14:25.890
are also on the order of
thousands of kilometers,

00:14:25.890 --> 00:14:28.260
but there is a time
variation on them

00:14:28.260 --> 00:14:31.680
that, for the LIGO detectors,
is on the order of seconds

00:14:31.680 --> 00:14:33.657
at most, really
tenths of a second

00:14:33.657 --> 00:14:35.490
at the current sensitivity
of the detectors,

00:14:35.490 --> 00:14:38.550
up to milliseconds.

00:14:38.550 --> 00:14:40.750
Way faster variation.

00:14:40.750 --> 00:14:43.890
So by looking for pieces
of what I can measure

00:14:43.890 --> 00:14:46.482
that vary on these length
scales and these time scales,

00:14:46.482 --> 00:14:47.940
I can separate it
from effects that

00:14:47.940 --> 00:14:53.490
are varying on these long time
scales and long length scales.

00:14:53.490 --> 00:14:57.237
So as I move forward
in this lecture,

00:14:57.237 --> 00:14:59.070
let me emphasize that
some of the things I'm

00:14:59.070 --> 00:15:01.148
going to introduce here are--

00:15:01.148 --> 00:15:03.190
first of all, they're a
little bit more advanced.

00:15:03.190 --> 00:15:06.930
You are certainly not
responsible for knowing

00:15:06.930 --> 00:15:09.400
the gory details of how
some of these tools I'm

00:15:09.400 --> 00:15:12.380
going to introduce are used.

00:15:12.380 --> 00:15:12.880
All right.

00:15:12.880 --> 00:15:14.590
So the point is,
once I've introduced

00:15:14.590 --> 00:15:17.680
these long scales and
these short scales,

00:15:17.680 --> 00:15:23.050
what we can then do is we
can always remove the wave,

00:15:23.050 --> 00:15:30.410
remove the oscillation by
introducing an averaging

00:15:30.410 --> 00:15:31.438
procedure.

00:15:37.300 --> 00:15:42.870
So if you imagine that you
average over a timescale that

00:15:42.870 --> 00:15:46.470
is several times the
wave-- excuse me--

00:15:46.470 --> 00:15:54.530
several times the period of the
wave and over a length scale

00:15:54.530 --> 00:15:58.940
that is several times the
wavelength of the wave.

00:15:58.940 --> 00:16:02.120
These are taken to be
shorter than the long scales,

00:16:02.120 --> 00:16:05.790
but longer than
the short scales.

00:16:05.790 --> 00:16:07.260
And so when you do that--

00:16:10.380 --> 00:16:13.590
let me put it this way.

00:16:13.590 --> 00:16:17.670
If I average-- so
these angle brackets

00:16:17.670 --> 00:16:20.450
are what I'm going to define
as my averaging procedure.

00:16:20.450 --> 00:16:22.950
I will make this a little bit
more quantitative in a moment.

00:16:36.210 --> 00:16:39.840
On length scale l
and timescale t,

00:16:39.840 --> 00:16:42.000
the background basically
doesn't change.

00:16:50.350 --> 00:16:53.630
So when I average it, I just
get the background back.

00:16:53.630 --> 00:16:57.480
On the other hand, my wave
oscillates a couple of times.

00:16:57.480 --> 00:17:01.410
So if I average
something that oscillates

00:17:01.410 --> 00:17:03.810
over a couple of
cycles, I get 0.

00:17:06.690 --> 00:17:08.250
So given what I can
actually measure,

00:17:08.250 --> 00:17:10.980
which is the spacetime or
things related to the spacetime,

00:17:10.980 --> 00:17:14.354
this averaging procedure lets
me pick out the background.

00:17:41.620 --> 00:17:43.760
The radiation is
then what I get when

00:17:43.760 --> 00:17:46.790
I subtract that average
bit from the field.

00:18:02.240 --> 00:18:05.663
So these are all things that,
as a theorist thinking about how

00:18:05.663 --> 00:18:07.580
someone is going to go
in and actually measure

00:18:07.580 --> 00:18:09.122
properties of the
gravitational wave,

00:18:09.122 --> 00:18:12.980
these are tools I can use
to separate one spatially

00:18:12.980 --> 00:18:15.580
and temporally varying
quantity from another.

00:18:15.580 --> 00:18:17.983
Now, here I'm going to
describe something that's

00:18:17.983 --> 00:18:20.150
a little bit more advanced
than we need to get into,

00:18:20.150 --> 00:18:21.660
but it's important to discuss.

00:18:21.660 --> 00:18:24.105
How do you actually
average a tensor like this?

00:18:24.105 --> 00:18:25.230
That's a little bit tricky.

00:18:28.880 --> 00:18:31.310
So the averaging was
first made rigorous.

00:18:31.310 --> 00:18:38.280
And there have been various
other mathematical formulations

00:18:38.280 --> 00:18:40.030
of this that are
presented over the years,

00:18:40.030 --> 00:18:42.613
but I like this particular one
because it's conceptually quite

00:18:42.613 --> 00:18:43.880
simple.

00:18:43.880 --> 00:18:51.230
It was first made rigorous by
Dieter Brill and James Hartle--

00:18:51.230 --> 00:18:54.610
Hartle is the author of a
nice elementary textbook

00:18:54.610 --> 00:18:57.680
on general relativity--

00:18:57.680 --> 00:18:59.330
in 1964.

00:18:59.330 --> 00:19:01.235
And the reference is
given in the notes.

00:19:01.235 --> 00:19:04.100
And what you basically
do is to define

00:19:04.100 --> 00:19:08.900
the average of a quantity
like the spacetime metric,

00:19:08.900 --> 00:19:11.450
you integrate it over
some proper volume

00:19:11.450 --> 00:19:18.980
in spacetime, proper 4 volume
with a particular weighting

00:19:18.980 --> 00:19:21.600
function.

00:19:21.600 --> 00:19:25.700
So this is something
that is defined such

00:19:25.700 --> 00:19:35.070
that if you integrate it over
that same region, you get 1.

00:19:35.070 --> 00:19:37.020
And it's taken to be
something that is--

00:19:37.020 --> 00:19:39.720
you can sort of think of as a
Gaussian in all four spacetime

00:19:39.720 --> 00:19:45.750
directions that
is peaked around--

00:19:45.750 --> 00:19:49.140
it's peaked at a
particular location,

00:19:49.140 --> 00:19:57.916
and it has a width of l in
all directions, l and t.

00:20:01.810 --> 00:20:03.760
We spent a lot of time
talking about what

00:20:03.760 --> 00:20:05.860
makes a tensor a tensor.

00:20:05.860 --> 00:20:08.020
And one of the things
that we discussed

00:20:08.020 --> 00:20:13.000
was the fact that when I am
working in curved space time

00:20:13.000 --> 00:20:17.010
and my basis objects
are functions,

00:20:17.010 --> 00:20:20.700
I can't really add a
tensor here to a tensor

00:20:20.700 --> 00:20:23.940
there because they live in
different tangent spaces.

00:20:23.940 --> 00:20:27.680
That's a poorly
defined operation.

00:20:27.680 --> 00:20:30.700
An integral is nothing more
than a sum on steroids.

00:20:30.700 --> 00:20:35.350
So how is it that I'm
allowed to do this?

00:20:35.350 --> 00:20:38.570
Well, the idea here
is this is not exact.

00:20:38.570 --> 00:20:39.780
OK?

00:20:39.780 --> 00:20:41.820
When one does this,
you will find--

00:20:41.820 --> 00:20:53.740
what comes out-- your average
tensor modulo corrections

00:20:53.740 --> 00:21:08.430
or errors that are of
order short length scale

00:21:08.430 --> 00:21:11.212
over long time length scale.

00:21:11.212 --> 00:21:13.170
This is the best you're
going to be able to do.

00:21:13.170 --> 00:21:14.850
You're always going
to be a little bit

00:21:14.850 --> 00:21:17.190
off when you define an
averaging procedure like this

00:21:17.190 --> 00:21:19.248
because by definition,
an average can't

00:21:19.248 --> 00:21:20.040
capture everything.

00:21:20.040 --> 00:21:21.207
That's why you're averaging.

00:21:21.207 --> 00:21:23.650
You're trying to actually
throw away some piece of it.

00:21:23.650 --> 00:21:28.140
So this allows us to
define our tensor calculus

00:21:28.140 --> 00:21:34.080
in this averaged way in a
very useful framework provided

00:21:34.080 --> 00:21:34.650
with--

00:21:34.650 --> 00:21:36.870
we just need to accept the
fact that there's always

00:21:36.870 --> 00:21:37.620
going to be--

00:21:37.620 --> 00:21:40.800
it really only makes
sense in this regime where

00:21:40.800 --> 00:21:43.210
we can cleanly separate our
length scales and our time

00:21:43.210 --> 00:21:44.700
scales.

00:21:44.700 --> 00:21:47.962
I emphasize this because
sometimes one does an analysis,

00:21:47.962 --> 00:21:49.920
and one finds things are
really weird going on.

00:21:49.920 --> 00:21:51.503
It's often useful
to sort of step back

00:21:51.503 --> 00:21:52.550
and say, wait a minute.

00:21:52.550 --> 00:21:54.300
I'm trying to describe
gravitational waves

00:21:54.300 --> 00:21:55.930
in a particular regime.

00:21:55.930 --> 00:21:58.110
Are these actually
gravitational waves?

00:21:58.110 --> 00:21:59.652
And you sort of look
at this, and you

00:21:59.652 --> 00:22:02.190
realize you've put yourself
into a regime where

00:22:02.190 --> 00:22:06.540
your perturbation is varying on
the same timescales and length

00:22:06.540 --> 00:22:08.250
scales as your background.

00:22:08.250 --> 00:22:11.670
And in fact, your amplitude
is no longer really small.

00:22:11.670 --> 00:22:12.900
You sort of go, oh, crap.

00:22:12.900 --> 00:22:14.910
What I've done here is
I've actually pushed this

00:22:14.910 --> 00:22:18.900
beyond the regime in which
the radiative approximation is

00:22:18.900 --> 00:22:20.050
valid.

00:22:20.050 --> 00:22:20.980
So bear this in mind.

00:22:20.980 --> 00:22:22.620
You're always
working-- you're always

00:22:22.620 --> 00:22:26.880
going to be working in
this approximative form.

00:22:26.880 --> 00:22:28.170
Suppose we have now done this.

00:22:28.170 --> 00:22:30.570
We have separated length scales.

00:22:30.570 --> 00:22:40.240
So we now have cleanly
and conceptually

00:22:40.240 --> 00:22:43.600
separated into background
and perturbation.

00:22:53.690 --> 00:22:55.490
Now what I would
like to do is just

00:22:55.490 --> 00:23:01.988
run through my exercise of
computing all the quantities

00:23:01.988 --> 00:23:04.030
that I need to do to
describe radiation-- really,

00:23:04.030 --> 00:23:07.400
all of my quantities that I need
to do to develop and then solve

