00:28:55.680 --> 00:28:56.670
you know what?

00:28:56.670 --> 00:29:01.700
Expand out all of these
covariant derivatives

00:29:01.700 --> 00:29:04.750
and then compare these terms.

00:29:04.750 --> 00:29:08.390
And this ends up being what
you get when the smoke clears.

00:29:08.390 --> 00:29:10.670
I go through this
one in some detail

00:29:10.670 --> 00:29:15.830
because simplifications of
this sort happen at every level

00:29:15.830 --> 00:29:16.630
as we move on.

00:29:16.630 --> 00:29:19.610
What we're basically going to
do is sort of brute force expand

00:29:19.610 --> 00:29:20.540
things.

00:29:20.540 --> 00:29:23.690
We'll find a term that looks
like just a pure background

00:29:23.690 --> 00:29:26.420
piece, and then there'll
be a whole bunch

00:29:26.420 --> 00:29:30.880
of little bits of crap that
are linear in the field h.

00:29:30.880 --> 00:29:32.960
And you can gather
them together and often

00:29:32.960 --> 00:29:35.370
write them in a form that's
prettier, kind of like this,

00:29:35.370 --> 00:29:38.720
where it's just sort of a shift
to the connection involving

00:29:38.720 --> 00:29:40.550
covariant derivatives.

00:29:40.550 --> 00:29:44.060
There's no great algorithm for
actually working all these guys

00:29:44.060 --> 00:29:45.230
out.

00:29:45.230 --> 00:29:47.360
Basically, you just
have a bit of labor

00:29:47.360 --> 00:29:49.590
to do to put them together.

00:29:49.590 --> 00:30:01.760
So let me write out a couple
